{"add":{"doc":{"id":"e7bc4fb40c3bf623d7f52c88852ad2d0a35c210ce54e9c8fbd5b1a27316b17a6","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Romanian_troops.jpg/220px-Romanian_troops.jpg","previous":["The Romanian Armed Forces consist of Land, Air, and Naval Forces, and are led by a Commander-in-chief under the supervision of the Ministry of Defense, and by the president as the Supreme Commander during wartime. The Armed Forces consist of approximately 15,000 civilians and 75,000 are military personnel—45,800 for land, 13,250 for air, 6,800 for naval forces, and 8,800 in other fields.[159] The total defence spending in 2007 accounted for 2.05% of total national GDP, or approximately US$2.9 billion, with a total of $11 billion spent between 2006 and 2011 for modernization and acquisition of new equipment.[160]"],"after":["The Land Forces have overhauled their equipment in the past few years, and are actively participating in the War in Afghanistan.[161] The Air Force currently operates modernized Soviet MiG-21 Lancer fighters which are due to be replaced by twelve F-16s, recently purchased.[162] The Air Force purchased seven new C-27J Spartan tactical airlifters,[163] while the Naval Forces acquired two modernized Type 22 frigates from the Royal Navy.[164] Romanian troops participated in the occupation of Iraq, reaching a peak of 730 soldiers before being slowly drawn down to 350 soldiers. Romania terminated its mission in Iraq and withdrew its last troops on 24 July 2009, among the last countries to do so. Romania currently has some 1,900 troops deployed in Afghanistan.[165] The Regele Ferdinand frigate participated in the 2011 military intervention in Libya.[166]"]}}}